            <div type="general">
               <p rendition="#slideshow">
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190825_091549199-1-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190825_091549199-1-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>View from the oldest mosque's tower</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190825_092317412-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190825_092317412-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Residents showing the oldest local mosque</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_103558119-1-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_103558119-1-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>On a bike tour through the palmery next to the mountains</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_090315598-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_090315598-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Researcher Franzi riding on the remains of a tractor</head>
                  </figure>
               </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">El Guettar, located in the southwest Tunisian governorate of Gafsa, is famous for its former natural water sources (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ʕyūn</hi>)<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">. </hi>Though they have dried out decades ago, El Guettar’s residential quarters are named after the numerous former springs. </p>
               <p>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_111649504-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_111649504-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Spring holes in the palmery</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_111816861-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_111816861-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Gathering around a former water source</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190829_090946792-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190829_090946792-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Dry riverbed</head>
                  </figure>
               </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">As the small town lies on the foot of a mountain range, its landscape's dry riverbeds are reminiscent of their water flows of former times. Even today, El Guettar is still a town with many green areas, such as palm forests, orchards and vast olive groves. Thus, olives – and its oil –, pistachios, dates, figs and cactus fruits are El Guettar’s most important agricultural products. </p>
               <p rendition="#slideshow">
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_101914929-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_101914929-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Impression of the diverse landscape</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_121522323-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_121522323-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Palm fronds with fruits</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_082147426-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_082147426-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Dates hanging on a palmtree</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_102036342-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_102036342-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Fresh cropped pistachios</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_101906894-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_101906894-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Cactus plant with Indian figs</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190826_105126837-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190826_105126837-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Tasty fresh fig</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190826_104835123-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190826_104835123-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Fig tree with fruits</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_102058123-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_102058123-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Olive tree with fruits</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190824_191856077-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190824_191856077-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Olive grove</head>
                  </figure>
               </p>
               <p>Since people produce their foodstuff mainly by themselves using traditional techniques, they also manufacture tools like millstones (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">rḥā</hi>). </p>
               <p>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190828_100041164-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190828_100041164-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>El Guettar. Millstone manufacturer</head>
                  </figure>
                  <figure>
                     <link target="IMG_20190828_100331624-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="IMG_20190828_100331624-scaled.jpg"/>
                     <head>Millstone</head>
                  </figure>
               </p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">For many residents of El Guettar, agriculture and livestock breeding form their livelihood. In addition to that, the local phosphate industry as well as the governorate’s capital Gafsa, which is just at a 20 km distance from El Guettar, provide jobs.</p>
               <p rendition="#slideshow">
                  <figure>
                     <link target="Guettar-dough.jpg"/>
                     <graphic url="Guettar-dough.jpg"/>
                     <head>Preparing the bread dough</head>
                  </figure>
